`(fun g => comp (id X) g) = id (Hom X c)`

But `Hom X c` is the type of homomorphisms from `X` to `c`. So `id (Hom X c)` is the identity function on the set of homomorphisms from `X` to `c`.

The function `fun g => comp (id X) g` takes a homomorphism `g` from `X` to `c` and composes it with `id X`. Since `X` is the domain of `g`, `id X` is the identity function on `X`. So `comp (id X) g` is just `g` itself.

Therefore, `fun g => comp (id X) g` is equal to `fun g => g`, which is the identity function on `Hom X c`. So the goal is indeed true.

